org.cast.cwm.service
Class ResponseService

java.lang.Object
  org.cast.cwm.service.ResponseService

public class ResponseService
extends Object

A Hibernate implementation of the service class used to save/load/modify Response objects. Eventually, this should be split into Abstract and HibernateImpl classes.

Get a single response by a given user for a given prompt. This assumes that only one such response should exist. If multiple responses are returned, an exception will be thrown. In such cases, use getResponsesForPrompt(IModel, IModel), or preferably, ISortableProvider. See getResponseProviderForPrompt(IModel, IModel).

getResponseCountForPrompt

public Long getResponseCountForPrompt(org.apache.wicket.model.IModel<? extends Prompt> mPrompt,
                                      IResponseType type,
                                      org.apache.wicket.model.IModel<? extends User> mUser)
Get the total number of valid responses for the given prompt. If a response type is specified, only responses of that type will be counted. If mUser is specified, then only responses by that user will be counted.

Parameters:
mPrompt - the prompt for which responses will be counted
type - the type of responses to count (null to count all)
mUser - the user whose responses will be counted, or null to count all users.
Returns:
the count

setResponseSortOrder

public void setResponseSortOrder(org.apache.wicket.model.IModel<? extends Prompt> mPrompt,
                                 org.apache.wicket.model.IModel<Response> mResponse,
                                 Integer index)
Uses Response#setSortOrder(Integer) to adjust the location of a Response in a list of responses for a given Prompt. Adjusts all affected Response objects whose sortOrder changes. Note 1: This method assumes that the response has already been persisted (and therefore attached to the prompt). Note 2: This method overrides any existing sortOrder values and re-indexes them into sequential order. This erases any drift from 'deleting' Responses, which does not cascade to the sortOrder and leaves gaps in the sequence. TODO: This has not been extensively tested.

Parameters:
iterator -
modelObject -
index - target index; null value appends to the end

deleteResponse

public void deleteResponse(org.apache.wicket.model.IModel<Response> r)
Delete a response from the datastore. This does not actually remove any data, but sets Response#setValid(boolean) to 'false.'

Parameters:
r - the response to be deleted
